<div id="review_2300202634" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2300202634" />
    <a title="Tanmay Jadhav" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/65664812-tanmay-jadhav"><img alt="Tanmay Jadhav" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1606054256p2/65664812.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2300202634?book_show_action=true">Feb 18, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tanmay Jadhav" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tanmay Jadhav" href="/user/show/65664812-tanmay-jadhav">Tanmay Jadhav</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2300202634" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer34807607232866027">Every time i pick up a Jhumpa Lahiri, i feel like i know what i&apos;m getting into and yet every time i find myself proven wrong. <br/><br/>I can ramble for hours about the story and nuances but to be honest the story isn&apos;t what makes the book special<br/><br/>Jhumpa&apos;s flowing texts with apparently irrelevant descriptions that confluence perfectly with the scenario or as a buildup is what makes her an irreplaceable part of literary history.<br/><br/>The way she can take you between generations and second person perspectives of a</span>
  <span id="freeText34807607232866027" style="display:none">Every time i pick up a Jhumpa Lahiri, i feel like i know what i'm getting into and yet every time i find myself proven wrong. <br /><br />I can ramble for hours about the story and nuances but to be honest the story isn't what makes the book special<br /><br />Jhumpa's flowing texts with apparently irrelevant descriptions that confluence perfectly with the scenario or as a buildup is what makes her an irreplaceable part of literary history.<br /><br />The way she can take you between generations and second person perspectives of all the characters involved is magical. And the way she puts you right in the middle of the story makes me cry quite often along with the characters. <br /><br />Jhumpa in my opinion paints human emotions like no one i've encountered yet. The way she develops and maintains undertones and core character themes makes you hate her and love her at the same time. <br /><br />I'm terribly sorry for turning this review into a fanboy rant. This book is everything you could ask for after "Namesake"<br /><br />It takes up so many backgrounds. From the Naxal uprising to the bonds of brothers to a compromise marriage that never takes course to the characters, old with regret, trying to set things right or at least get some closure. <br /><br />This is a heart wrenching tale of normal people who find themselves in extraordinary circumstances trying to live normal lives but failing at it. This ability of Jhumpa to create something extraordinary from the lives of normal people is my favorite thing about her. <br /><br />Please read this.<br /><br />Cheers,<br />Tanmay J<br /><br />P.s. 4 stars because i feel like the author had lost her touch in the middle chapters and wasted it on story lines that did not matter much. The book was flawless otherwise.</span>
