    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_676708518" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/676708518" />
    <a title="Chrissie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie"><img alt="Chrissie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1321799585p2/632247.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/676708518?book_show_action=true">Apr 16, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chrissie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chrissie" href="/user/show/632247-chrissie">Chrissie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=ireland">ireland</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=india">india</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=immigrants">immigrants</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=audible">audible</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=contemp-novel">contemp-novel</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=love">love</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=usa">usa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=lgtb">lgtb</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=hf">hf</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/632247-chrissie?shelf=life-stages">life-stages</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer676708518" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7087120445249086764">I should feel more attached to the characters than I do. <br/><br/>The story is about two Indian brothers born fifteen months apart, the first in 1943 and the second in 1945. Despite their differences in personality, they are close, very close. The story continues more than a decade into the 21st century. They are born in Calcutta. The book concerns sibling relationships, what binds them and what divides them. One brother knows his goals and goes after them. Some might call this self-centered. The other h</span>
  <span id="freeText7087120445249086764" style="display:none">I should feel more attached to the characters than I do. <br /><br />The story is about two Indian brothers born fifteen months apart, the first in 1943 and the second in 1945. Despite their differences in personality, they are close, very close. The story continues more than a decade into the 21st century. They are born in Calcutta. The book concerns sibling relationships, what binds them and what divides them. One brother knows his goals and goes after them. Some might call this self-centered. The other has goals too but is more flexible in how to achieve them and more conscious of how his actions influence others. Their choices have repercussions on each other, on who each one will marry and on other members of the family--for generations to come. <br /><br />The backdrop is set by the historical events unfolding in India and the US during the brothers’ lives. One brother stays in India. One moves to America. In India, there arises the Naxalite Movement and then the Partition. In the US we see the Vietnam War and growth of flower power in the 1960s and early 1970s. We observe how this affects life on school campuses. These events are the backdrop, the central theme is however the relationships that arise. <br /><br />The author is known for writing about immigrants, and she does that here too. Each immigrant has a different story to tell. Their stories do not end with their own lives. The lives of their children and grandchildren are affected too. Immigration is an important component of the story told here. <br /><br />One woman comes to affect the lives of the two brothers. Her actions are central to the story told. Her behavior is, in my view, not properly explored. I want more of her thoughts. If I am to accept what she does, I need to understand how she is thinking. I can think through what she does, logically, in my own head, but to really understand her I need to have access to <u>her</u> thoughts. I have a very hard time accepting the manner in which she <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[abandons her daughter <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>. Could the schism be at least partially a result of differences in personal chemistry? Nothing is said of this. The book is over, and I am still looking for an answer. This I find unsatisfactory!<br /><br />The story uses flashbacks. As events occur readers are not given full information. Flashbacks later fill in the gaps. I do not like this. To fully understand a character’s motivation, I need as much information as possible as events unfold, not later! The flashbacks add clarity, but the information provided comes at the wrong point. The telling becomes disjointed. The flashbacks sum up, explain, what has happened earlier. Consequently, earlier events are told rather than shown. In them, dialogue is often lacking. Dialogue pulls a reader into a story, and so this we miss. The flashbacks do not improve the telling of the story. <br /><br />The story is too long and drawn out, partially, as a result of the flashbacks. <br /><br />There is a coldness, a reserve, a lack of spontaneity in the characters. This puts up a border between me and them. None, other than <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[the younger brother, who dies early in the story <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span>, feel alive to me. <br /><br />There is no humor whatsoever. There is a restraint, a lack of vivacity, a depressing tone in the telling that I find draining. <br /><br />I cannot give the book more stars. The topics covered have potential. The potential I find unfulfilled. <br /><br />Suni Malhotra narrates the audiobook very well. His tone fits the mood of the characters and the story. It is not the narrator’s fault that characters do not come alive. His reading mirrors the author’s lines. Four stars for the audio narration.<br /><br />*****************<br /><br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/17262100.The_Lowland" title="The Lowland by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">The Lowland</a> 3 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/33917.The_Namesake" title="The Namesake by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">The Namesake</a> 3 stars<br />*<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/5439.Interpreter_of_Maladies" title="Interpreter of Maladies by Jhumpa Lahiri" rel="nofollow noopener">Interpreter of Maladies</a> 2 star</span>
  <a data-text-id="7087120445249086764" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

